		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.75]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Stabo&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Roos's GUIDE TO PHAT PLAT - well sort of......<br><br>This is a repost of a message I wrote way back in June/July sometime.&nbsp;&nbsp;I used my little system for about 6 months and I've made about 75-100k doing it. I don't do it so much anymore because most upgrades I want at this point are NoDrop<br><br>I know a few of you read this the first time I posted it because within a week or two of posting the merchant competition I was facing in the bazaar doubled or tripled.  Doh!! Serves me right. Anyway, always happy to help other warriors, we have it hard enough as it is.<br><br>**********************************************<br><br>While some of the people on here have twinked their characters quite a bit with money from their main, others of us - like me - with only one character, have had to find creative ways to make money. <br><br>I started out just buying and selling stuff in the bazaar.  Yes, it's a pain, and yes it's time consuming, but the money is real good. Here’s how I do it. <br><br>First I'd do a search on a specific slot and stat and set a price range above what I could afford - feet and AC and price range 0 – 500 pp. Then I'd look at all the items for sale. I would only consider buying items if they fit two criteria, 1) there had to be 3-4+ sellers of the exact same item &amp; 2) There had to be a low price outlier – someone selling way below all the rest. <br><br>For example, Some random item might be selling for 300, 290, 310 and 225. I would buy it for 225 and &quot;flip it&quot;. Setting my price so that I was still 5-10% below the next cheapest. In this example say 275. What the item is, is unimportant. <br><br>80% of the time I would sell the item within a week. I would have 20-30 items in my trader, so things were constantly coming and going. Occasionally, I'd have to lower a price and either break even or lose a little, but my winners outnumbered my losers 4-1. I actually created a little excel spreadsheet which I printed out with the following columns. (date, price I paid, average price in bazaar, my selling price, and profit made). I never sold my own loot to merchants if people were buying/selling in the bazaar. <br><br>Also, I also always set my prices the lowest, because I want to turn things over quick - 3 consecutive quick sales in a week with a 100 profit on each is better, than waiting a longer time for that 150 profit. <br><br>Anyway, I started out selling noob armor – warrior stuff mostly because I knew the gear – and slowly moved up. A side benefit was that I’d often upgrade my own gear when I spotted a great deal. I don’t think I’ve paid the “average market price” for anything on my guy. <br><br>Once I got a decent amount of cash this way I started doing what Gulug has suggested. Buying and selling the items that trade-skillers use and which are in constant demand. People who farm the stuff often don’t want to wait around to sell it, so they’ll dump it all in the bazaar at half off the normal price. I’ll just buy it by the stack (or occasionally buy them one by one), raise the price by 50% and resell them all over the next couple days. <br><br>The key is to know what the common prices are. Once a day for a week spend 5 minutes in the bazaar and check prices on your server for the various silks, skins, hides, velium, acrylia, and stuff like that. <br><br>Setting your prices<br>With the trade-skill stuff I DON’T want to be the low priced leader. When people buy, they buy a ton. I’ve sold 4 or 5 stacks of silk at one time and 8 - 10 stacks of acrylia at once. And my prices are never the lowest. But, if you’re not selling it in a week you’re prices are probably to high, and if you sold out day one, they might be too low. <br><br>I will say though that tradeskill components sell a lot faster than regular equipment. I guess the high level smiths and tailors have more money than time. So you may want to skip the armor &amp; equipment selling, though it worked for me. <br><br>I’m not super rich, but I’ve got over 35k in the bank and all my equipment by doing what I’ve described. <br><br>One catch, though the money is good, the problem that I’ve found is that I can easily spend all my time in the bazaar. What’s the fun in that right? So to keep the money flowing while I’m leveling I usually hunt in areas with good loot drops. Tribals in DSP is a favorite (level 30-40's) – the acrylia drops sell real easy in the bazaar. Also, sometimes my group mates are planning on selling their looted acrylia to merchants – who pay low prices – so I’ll offer them more than what merchants pay and then resell in bazaar. <br><br>The one thing that is key to all this though is a good internet connection. DSL, Cable, etc. Otherwise your trader is offline too much of the time. <br><br>Best of luck, <br>Roos<br>Barb Warrior 55</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >1 Replies</td></tr></table><table width="100%"><tr><td class=mhback>&nbsp;</td><td class=mhback >Thread Subject</a></td><td class=mhback>Started by</a></td><td class=mhback>Replies</a></td><td class=mhback>Last Post</a></td><td class=mhback>Rating</a></td></tr><tr class=mlr>
